20back%2C%20likely%20because%20of%20the%20particles%20spewed%20by%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Ftonga-volcano-eruption-ruptures-giant-undersea-internet-cable-2022-1%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EHunga%20Tonga%20underwater%20volcano%20eruption%3C%2Fa%3E%20in%202022.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThat's%20why%20it's%20important%20to%20keep%20an%20eye%20on%20particles%20in%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fstratosphere-shrinking-greenhouse-gas-emissions-climate-change-2021-5%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Estratosphere%3C%2Fa%3E.%20These%20nanometer-sized%20flecks%2C%20which%20naturally%20come%20from%20meteors%20crashing%20into%20the%20planet%2C%20can%20dramatically%20change%20the%20stratosphere's%20chemistry.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EClouds%20don't%20usually%20tend%20to%20form%20in%20the%20stratosphere%2C%20because%20it's%20much%20drier%20than%20the%20troposphere%2C%20where%20most%20clouds%20are%20born.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBy%20bringing%20in%20elements%20you%20wouldn't%20usually%20see%20in%20the%20sky%2C%20like%20metals%2C%20these%20particles%20can%20combine%20with%20the%20sulfuric%20acid%20naturally%20present%20in%20the%20stratosphere%20to%20create%20a%20chemical%20reaction%20that%20can%20suck%20up%20passing%20water%20vapor%2C%20creating%20an%20ice%20crystal.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThat%2C%20in%20turn%2C%20can%20spark%20a%20chain%20reaction%20that%20creates%20rainbow-colored%20polar%20stratospheric%20clouds.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EOn%20their%20own%2C%20these%20stunning%20clouds%20are%20harmless%2C%20but%20they%20can%20be%20terrifying%20when%20mixed%20with%20human-made%20gases.%20The%20clouds'%20edges%20offer%20perfect%20conditions%20to%20turn%20damaging%20chlorines%20and%20bromides%20into%20their%20active%2C%20ozone-busting%20form.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%225477%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22Rainbow%20colored%20clouds%20are%20seen%20strewn%20in%20the%20skies.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F658c172f1c5c7b8c9a0c2a8b%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%223651%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EPolar%20stratospheric%20clouds%20(PSCs)%20are%20seen%20in%20the%20sky%20over%20Jukkasjarvi%2C%20northern%20Sweden%2C%20on%20December%2017%2C%202023%20in%20Jukkasjarvi%2C%20Sweden.%3Cp%3ERoy%20Rochlin%2FGetty%20Images%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Ch2%3EMetal%20from%20satellites%20and%20spacecraft%20is%20vaporizing%20into%20the%20atmosphere%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EMurphy%20and%20his%20colleagues%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Frocket-satellite-metals-polluting-earth-stratosphere-2023-10%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Erecently%20conducted%20a%20survey%3C%2Fa%3E%20of%20the%20state%20of%20stratospheric%20particles%20over%20Alaska%20using%20a%20sensitive%20detector%20aboard%20NASA's%20WB-57%20high-altitude%20research%20plane.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20findings%2C%20published%20in%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.pnas.org%2Fdoi%2F10.1073%2Fpnas.2313374120%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Epeer-reviewed%20journal%20PNAS%3C%2Fa%3E%20in%20October%202023%2C%20revealed%20that%20about%2010%25%20of%20the%20stratospheric%20sulfuric%20acid%20particles%20they%20picked%20up%20could%20not%20be%20explained%20by%20natural%20causes.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BWe%20weren't%20really%20looking%20for%20spacecraft%2C%20but%20it%20became%20apparent%20in%20the%20data%20that%20there%20were%20elements%20that%20couldn't%20be%20coming%20from%20the%20meteors%2C%26quot%3B%20Murphy%20told%20BI.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%221999%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22A%20picture%20from%20inside%20a%20cockpit%20shows%20the%20sky%20and%20clouds%20below%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F65e03c97ce7f1785b2e4d230%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22609%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EThe%20view%20from%20NASA's%20WB-57%20cockpit%20during%20a%20SABRE%20high-altitude%20research%20flight.%3Cp%3EThomas%20Parent%2C%20NASA%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20particles%20contained%20%26quot%3Bfar%20too%20much%20aluminum%2C%20far%20too%20much%20lithium%2C%20far%20too%20much%20of%20a%20few%20other%20elements%20to%20be%20coming%20from%20meteors%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ETwo%20elements%20found%20in%20the%20particles%2C%20niobium%20and%20hafnium%2C%20were%20particularly%20surprising%2C%20Murphy%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcsl.noaa.gov%2Fnews%2F2023%2F388_1016.html%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Esaid.%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThese%20don't%20occur%20naturally%2C%20but%20have%20to%20be%20refined%2C%20the%20scientists%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThe%20combination%20of%20aluminum%20and%20copper%2C%20plus%20niobium%20and%20hafnium%2C%20which%20are%20used%20in%20heat-resistant%2C%20high-performance%20alloys%2C%20pointed%20us%20to%20the%20aerospace%20industry%2C%26quot%3B%20Murphy%20added.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%224270%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22A%20graphic%20shows%20how%20meteors%20and%20spacecraft%20reentry%20could%20spark%20metal%20particles%20in%20the%20stratosphere.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F65e03d0d6080194819fb1a0c%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%223515%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EA%20graphic%20illustrates%20where%20metal%20particles%20in%20the%20stratosphere%20could%20come%20from.%3Cp%3EChelsea%20Thompson%2C%20NOAA%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3ERight%20now%2C%20we%20simply%20don't%20know%20what%20these%20new%20particles%20could%20do.%20But%20scientists%20are%20eager%20to%20figure%20it%20out.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThis%20is%20a%20new%20problem%20and%20we're%20just%20beginning%20to%20understand%20it%2C%26quot%3B%20said%20Murphy.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThey%20may%20be%20able%20to%20spark%20polar%20stratospheric%20clouds.%20If%20so%2C%20this%20could%20be%20a%20big%20problem%20in%20the%20short%20term%2C%20Martin%20Chipperfield%2C%20a%20professor%20of%20atmospheric%20sciences%20from%20the%20University%20of%20Leeds%2C%20UK%2C%20told%20BI.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThe%20timescale%20for%20the%20ozone%20hole%20to%20disappear%20is%20about%202060%20based%20on%20current%20predictions%20because%20the%20chlorine%20is%20going%20down%20very%2C%20very%20slowly%2C%26quot%3B%20said%20Chipperfield%2C%20who%20was%20not%20involved%20in%20the%20study.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BSo%20that%20still%20gives%20plenty%20of%20scope%20in%20the%20short%20term%2C%20if%20we%20greatly%20increase%20the%20burnout%20of%20space%20debris%20over%20next%20couple%20of%20decades%2C%20for%20the%20ozone%20hole%20get%20worse%20before%20it%20gets%20better%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThese%20new%20particles%20could%20also%20migrate%20to%20the%20troposphere%2C%20where%20they%20might%20influence%20the%20formation%20of%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Fprofiles%2Ffionagh-thomson-447864%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Efeathery%20cirrus%20clouds%3C%2Fa%3E.%20Unlike%20other%20clouds%2C%20cirrus%20clouds%20retain%20heat%20in%20our%20atmosphere%2C%20which%20could%20worsen%20the%20climate%20crisis.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIt's%20also%20possible%20that%20the%20particles%20could%20create%20a%20completely%20new%20phenomenon.%20Or%20they%20could%20do%20nothing%20at%20all.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ETheir%20composition%20is%20unique%2C%20so%20it's%20unclear%20what%20to%20expect.%20Murphy%20said%20scientists%20will%20have%20to%20do%20experiments%20in%20the%20lab%20to%20test%20this%20out.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BIt's%20very%20important%20to%20understand%20it%20because%20the%20space%20industry%20is%20growing%20so%20rapidly%2C%26quot%3B%20Murphy%20told%20BI.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BIf%20there%20are%20impacts%2C%20you'd%20rather%20understand%20it%20now%20before%20it%20grows%20than%20after%20it's%20already%20grown%20a%20lot.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3EWe're%20realizing%20how%20little%20we%20know%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EWith%20launch%20costs%20going%20down%2C%20the%20number%20of%20satellites%20orbiting%20the%20planet%20is%20only%20expected%20to%20grow%20to%20over%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.gao.gov%2Fproducts%2Fgao-22-105166%23%3A~%3Atext%3DRocket%2520launches%2520and%2520satellite%2520reentries%2Cemissions%2520could%2520mitigate%2520the%2520effects.%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%2050%2C000%20%3C%2Fa%3Eby%202030%2C%20up%20from%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Forbit.ing-now.com%2Flow-earth-orbit%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eabout%208%2C000%20now.%3C%2Fa%3E%20Many%20of%20these%20satellites%20are%20expected%20to%20have%20a%20short%20lifetime.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BIf%20you%20multiply%20those%20numbers%20out%2C%20a%20satellite%20will%20be%20reentering%20the%20atmosphere%20on%20average%20about%20once%20an%20hour%2C%26quot%3B%20said%20Murphy.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWithin%20the%20next%20few%20decades%2C%20Murphy%20and%20his%20co-authors%20estimate%20aerospace%20debris%20could%20make%20up%2050%25%20of%20the%20particles%20in%20the%20stratosphere%2C%20which%20makes%20the%20need%20to%20understand%20what%20they%20do%20even%20more%20pressing.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%221024%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22An%20illustration%20of%20thousands%20of%20dots%20around%20the%20Earth%20shows%20the%20density%20of%20satellites%20in%20the%20sky.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F65e041fece7f1785b2e4d242%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221024%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EAn%20illustration%20shows%20satellites%20around%20the%20Earth%20in%202019.%20Each%20dot%20represents%20one%20satellite%2C%20and%20is%20not%20scaled%20to%20size.%3Cp%3ENASA%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3ESpacecraft%20decommissioning%20is%20only%20part%20of%20the%20equation%2C%20said%20Chipperfield.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThere's%20an%20increasing%20number%20of%20rocket%20launches%20for%20small%20satellites%20and%20tourism%2C%20which%20burn%20kerosene%20or%20other%20fuels%20that%20emissions%20in%20the%20atmosphere.%20Then%20some%20satellites%20and%20orbit%20have%20fuel%20like%20iodine%20that%20can%20come%20back%20to%20the%20atmosphere.%20And%20then%20the%20demise%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BI%20think%20the%20whole%20life%20cycle%20of%20satellites%20is%20definitely%20one%20to%20watch%2C%20and%20this%20burn%20up%20is%20part%20of%20that%2C%26quot%3B%20said%20Chipperfield.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EScientists%20are%20also%20seriously%20considering%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fgeoengineering-atmosphere-clouds-harvard-2018-4%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Egeoengineering%20the%20atmosphere%3C%2Fa%3E%20to%20help%20shield%20our%20planet%20from%20the%20heat%20of%20the%20sun%20by%20sending%20billions%20of%20particles%20of%20sulfuric%20acid%20into%20the%20stratosphere.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EFor%20Murphy%2C%20this%20all%20goes%20to%20show%20just%20how%20little%20we%20know%20about%20how%20humans%20are%20affecting%20the%20stratosphere%20as%20more%20forays%20are%20reaching%20for%20the%20skies.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThat%20there%20was%20still%20a%20surprise%20in%20our%20understanding%20of%20the%20composition%20of%20particles%20in%20the%20stratosphere%20is%20relevant%20to%20conversations%20about%20adding%20more%2C%26quot%3B%20said%20Murphy.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%3ERead%20the%20original%20article%20on%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fsatellites-burn-atmosphere-particles-stratosphere-climate-ozone-2024-2%5C%22%3EBusiness%20Insider%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1709386561000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F65e191f590413ab8e1d81833%3Fformat%3Djpeg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fsatellites-burn-atmosphere-particles-stratosphere-climate-ozone-2024-2%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22Satellites%20burning%20in%20our%20atmosphere%20leave%20metal%20particles%20in%20the%20stratosphere%2C%20and%20scientists%20don't%20know%20if%20these%20could%